{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"131c82f4-0a41-4d07-a45e-3aa69e123fed","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but I can tell you exactly what you need to configure to publish a C# MCP server as a `dotnet tool`:\n\n### In your `.csproj`, add these properties:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- Required NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n\n  <!-- Must be Exe for stdio transport -->\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points:\n\n1. **`PackAsTool`** — marks the project as a .NET tool so `dotnet pack` produces an installable package.\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users will run (e.g., `my-mcp-server`).\n3. **`OutputType` must be `Exe`** — required for stdio transport.\n\n### Publish steps:\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push to NuGet.org (get API key from https://www.nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run with:\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server\n```\n\nThat's the minimum configuration. Want me to update your actual `.csproj` file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"463db427-6a4b-4c01-99b8-55ff31258d15","outputTokens":474,"requestId":"CC28:1D180A:7F05882:8D5DEAB:69EAC228"},"id":"350b8c68-6be7-4040-a76d-86d4bf327381","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:06:57.616Z","parentId":"56264154-839a-443f-a91d-90abe3270c59"}
